# 2.1 Creating an Array

# Array is a data structure used to store many items in once place 

Shopping = ['bread', 'butter', 'cheese']

#We can create an empty array

Empty = []

#We can also create an array used to store data later:

Temperature = [0] * 365 
#This creates an array full of 365 0s 

# 2.2 Accessing Array Values

#How do we talk to arrays?
#Each element of an arrary is assigned a number called an index, starting from 0 as integers
#In Shopping, bread is 0, butter is 1 and cheese is 2. We can access a part of an array by quoting its index

Shopping[1]  #This is butter

#We cab change arrary elements as if they were seperate variables. Say we want to record
#On the 42nd day of measurement air temp was 25 degrees

Temperature[42] = 25    #On a side note maybe the textbook forgot that day 1 of the year is day 0??? Shouldn't it be 43

# 2.3 Modifying Arrays - We can add stuff to an array

Shopping += ['eggs']

Shopping.insert(0, 'ham')   # Textbook does not mention this but its a much better way in my opinion

Shopping = Shopping[1::]  #One way I learnt to slice arrarys 

# 2.4 Iteration over an array

N = len(Shopping)   #counts the number of elements in an arrary 

print(N)


#Number of days with negative air temp, lets make something up...

Temperature[30] = -5

def numberofnegs(Temperature):
    total = 0
    for day in Temperature:
        if day < 0:
            total += 1
    return total

print(numberofnegs(Temperature))


